Consider another \delta -functor S^\bullet  with a natural transformation f : T^0 \to  S^0. We now have a diagram



        \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

  \begin {tikzcd}
  {T^0 I} & {T^0 Y} & {T^1 X} \\
  {S^0 I} & {S^0 Y} & {S^1 X}
  \arrow [from=1-1, to=1-2]
  \arrow [from=1-1, to=2-1]
  \arrow ["\delta ", two heads, from=1-2, to=1-3]
  \arrow [from=1-2, to=2-2]
  \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
  \arrow ["\delta "', from=2-2, to=2-3]
\end {tikzcd}



where we can fill the vertical map on the right, because the composite of the lower left route is zero on the kernel of \delta  : T^0 Y \to  T^1 X, and uniqueness follows from epimorphism. This then yields a transformation T^1 \to  S^1, we need to prove itâ€™s natural and does not depend on the chosen I. Then we can repeat the move to extend to arbitrary degrees.

Given a morphism \varphi : X \to X' and the corresponding monomorphisms X \to I, X' \to I', we can replace X \to I with X \to I \times I' since both components of the map are sent to 0 by T^0, an additive functor. This together with the projection map I \times I' \to I forms a commutative square. Taking the cokernel we also have an induced map \psi : Y \to Y'.
This leads to a 3-dimensional diagram
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd} {T^0 Y} && {T^1 X} \\ & {T^0 Y'} && {T^1 X'} \\ {S^0 Y} && {S^1 X} \\ & {S^0 Y'} && {S^1 X'} \arrow ["\delta ", two heads, from=1-1, to=1-3] \arrow ["{T^0 \psi }"', from=1-1, to=2-2] \arrow ["f"', from=1-1, to=3-1] \arrow ["{T^1 \varphi }", from=1-3, to=2-4] \arrow [from=1-3, to=3-3] \arrow ["\delta "{pos=0.3}, two heads, from=2-2, to=2-4] \arrow ["f"'{pos=0.3}, from=2-2, to=4-2] \arrow [from=2-4, to=4-4] \arrow [from=3-1, to=3-3] \arrow ["{S^0 \psi }"', from=3-1, to=4-2] \arrow ["{S^1 \varphi }", from=3-3, to=4-4] \arrow ["\delta "', from=4-2, to=4-4] \end {tikzcd}
where all but the right face commutes. After composing with \delta : T^0 Y \to T^1 X, we can use all five commutative squares to prove that the two compositions are equal. And since the morphism is epimorphic, the right square commutes as expected.
